<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Loramin at October 16, 2004 06:07 PM</strong></p>
<p>"All class bickery aside, if our primary problem is being LFG for too long, what can we do to help?<br />
1. Change class perception. Argue with group leaders and tell them to try out non-standard group configurations."  As I said before, perceptions != reality.  However, they are based off of reality, perhaps with some sort of lag for people to realize that X class got some new power or something.  Until the reality (that certain classes are better for the vast majority of current content) changes, ie. until Druids really are as useful as Clerics in most of the zones people want to hunt in, nobody is going to be able to change anyone's perception.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Loramin at October 16, 2004 06:14 PM</strong></p>
<p>"2. Build our own groups based on general requirements: Tank, Healer, Crowd Control, Damage."  In fact, I used to do this, when I was impatient and wanted to start a group (now I'm just lazy and wait LFG).  If I saw that no clerics were LFG (since Clerics were always everyone's first choice, and I was often asked by some other class I'd invite "do you have a cleric yet?"), I'd start sending tells to druids.  However, I couldn't just say "want to do a hard LDoN?" (as I would to a cleric), because when I did that they would assume we had a cleric already and some would actually yell at me when they discovered they were the main healer.  So instead I'd ask, "hey would you like to be main healer in an LDoN hard?" and reasonably often I'd hear "no thanks, I can't heal in hards."  Another common response (besides just "sure," which I did hear a lot too) was "how many hp does the tank have?"  Their logic here was that they recognized their own inferiority as a healer, but new they could still manage as long as they had a sufficiently superior tank to balance things out.  In contrast, out of the many clerics I invited (as I said I picked them first over druids) I only ever once heard one of them ask this question.<br />
</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Loramin at October 16, 2004 06:47 PM</strong></p>
<p>"3. Think up new ways to build groups."  Two more stories: 1)  I recently had the idea of trying to form a variant AE group with a bunch of melees using AE proc weapons, and I discussed the idea with a variety of players I knew, including the main tank in the 2nd (used to be 1st) most uber guild on our server.  Everyone who had never considered the idea doubted it would work, while everyone who had looked in to it previously was certain that it wouldn't.  My uber warrior friend had already learned a lot about this idea, and informed me that while variants of it had been tried many times, the only time they had ever worked was in early Luclin era, before the rampage AA was nerfed.  2)  Another alternative group (back during Luclin) was discovered by a shaman on a PvP server: the shaman/bard AE duo. He discovered that only 4 mobs could attack a single PC, and that a bard with Torpor on him could survive indefinitely with 4 FG shrooms beating on him, if they were slowed.  So the shaman could chain pull mushroom patches (no matter how many shrooms were already on the bard) with AE slow, and the bard would peel them with AE damage songs, and both got great exp.  But as you have probably noticed, any number of mobs can now beat on a PC, because when SOE discovered this AE group they promptly nerfed it.  The moral of these stories: there are creative and inventive people out there who are desperately trying to break the holy trinity mentality to group making.  But it doesn't matter how creative you get, you can't change the basic rules of the game, and ATM those rules make holy trinity groups the best (except maybe for traditional AE groups, which require 2/3 of the trinity).  And if anyone ever does discover a new type of group and shares it, SOE is all but guaranteed to find an exploit in it somewhere and nerf things such that the group is no longer viable.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Loramin at October 16, 2004 08:37 PM</strong></p>
<p>"What other suggestions do you have?"  All other things being equal, the holy trinity group always has been and continues to be the best group in EQ for the majority of the content.  Best at getting exp, loot, adv. points, whatever.  This is because the design of the game creates the basic archetypes you described, and the trinity is based on specialization: warriors tank better than any class, enchanters do crowd control better than any class, and clerics heal better than any class.  Just add 3 of the DPS class du jour, hit combine, and you're done. Once you understand this, you can see that every other class is an inferior alternative, because they aren't specialized and that is the true heart of the problem.  But the level of specialization, and thus inferiority, varies.  If you compare druids and clerics on healing (before AAs and focus effects, which just exagerate the differences), you see that both classes can cast a CH, in 10 seconds, using 400 mana.  But the cleric's (level 39) CH heals 7500 HP, while the druid's (level 58)CH heals only 2925 HP, less than half.  For quick heals both can use a level 68 spell to heal in 3.75 seconds. The druid's only heals 2420 HP, while the cleric's heals 3770 HP.  The druid's is a little cheaper (627 mana, vs. 740), but the cleric's quick heal is more efficient (5.1 HP/M vs. 3.9).  The healer is one of the most essential role in EQ, but as long as a druid can't CH even half as many HP as a cleric, there will be only one choice for this role.  For their specialization in healing, clerics get first pick.  For their lack of specialization, druids get ... ports.  This IMHO, is grossly out of balance.  In contrast, there are three choices for tanks, and while warriors can take take the most damage, the knights can take almost as much.  Plus, the knight's can generally gain agro better, and have significant utiltiy abilties, while the warrior doesn't.  So while the warrior is generally the preferred tank, some groups might prefer a knight, and all three are close to being equally desired.  The warrior may be specialized, but he is not really much more specialized than the Pali or SK, and whatever lack of specialization they have they make up for with relevant powers.  So, IMHO, what SOE ultimately needs to do is make several viable alternatives for the roles of healer and crowd control, the way they have with tank (though I'd love to see another tank class too).  There are four or less viable options for every role, except for DPS: by my count there are about 9, or 6 if you only count the ones with no other group role.  Without fail, you will always find members of this archetype LFG.  These classes need to be given the ability to fufill other roles.  What if rangers could tank, wizards could mez and necros could heal?  I think what would happen is a lot less people would be LFG.</p>
