<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by Siriln at October 17, 2004 02:00 PM</strong></p>
<p>Arguing with group leaders is all well and good, but do you want to do it with every single group you get?  And as for all classes having LFG problems...  Clerics occasionally do sit LFG for an hour or two.  And if you check the statments box I'll wager most of them are asking for a specific type of group.  Compare that to the fact that many classes average several hours LFG.  And the problem everyone seems to forget with non-traditional groups is that they'll still need buffs from the very classes they aren't relying on.  Ever seen a caster try to function without KEi for an extended amount of time?  Or a melee without Virtue?  It's possible, but downtime is ungodly long and these types of groups have insane amounts of recovery time if something goes wrong.</p>

<p>As a wizard, finding a group in under 2 hours is a thing of wonder, and happens about once a month.  I usually average about 3 hours LFG, because that's how long I'm willing to wait around before playing on an alt that's a more popular class.  My record was 12 straight hours LFG, while I kited to 62 in Natimbi.  Not a single tell the entire time.  Several other of the DPS classes have similar problems.  (No, I don't have a reputation on my server that I know of, I just know a handful of people the right level to group with, so PU groups for me :).)</p>

<p>Certain classes are Sony's golden children, and to a lesser extent that of the players as well.  Problems with bards, wizards, rangers, etc. are routinely ignored by Sony, and if complaints are voiced, the most common answer from players who don't have characters of that class is: "well go play something else."  But the minute anything resembling a nerf happens to clerics or enchanters, entire servers are up in arms.</p>

<p>When entire classes are so disposable that a highly flagged wizard or ranger is told to throw away two years of development but any 60+ enchanter or cleric is begged to remain in the game, I think things are little skewed.</p>
<p class="posted"><strong>Posted by <a target="_blank" title="http://www.furyoffaith.org" href="http://mobhunter.com/mt/mobhunter_post21.cgi?__mode=red;id=469">Eliyas</a> at October 18, 2004 08:18 AM</strong></p>
<p>I was a little nervous last night. Did an LGuk Collection Adventure with 5 people ranging in level from 65-69. Everone was equipped appropriately to their level. The makeup of the group was this: Druid, Enchanter, Bard, 2 Rangers. We had one death, finished the adventure with 20 minutes remaining.</p>

<p>Granted, we play together often and each knows their role very well. However, each class was able to hold their own without the standard "Cleric" and "Tank" classes. </p>

<p>I liked being nervous. I was more emotionally invested in this adventure because there was a chance of not succeeding. It made our success that much sweeter.</p>

<p>Doing this adventure with a Cleric, Tank, Chanter and DPS would have been easier, but much more hum-drum. I don't play this game to experience hum-drum.</p>

<p>In summary, I think the classes are tuned very well given the complexity and scope of the game. In addition, it is the players themselves who make this game exciting or boring, based on their own perceptions of what classes are appropriate for a particular group. The fewer people who fall into the Tank, Cleric, CC/Slower mind set, the better.</p>
